	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Pacific region: State support extended to avert crisis in Fijian sugar sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 February 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In December 2010, the Fijian permanent secretary responsible for sugar, Major Manasa Vaniqi, revealed that the ‘bulk of the $123 million allocated to the Sugar Industry in the 2011 national budget will be used to pay off the debts of the Fiji Sugar Corporation’. Part of it, however, will be used to ‘improve the operation of the mills’. In addition, financial assistance is also provided to ‘the supply of fertilizer to cane farmers’ ($9m) and ‘cane farm development’ ($2m). Permanent Secretary Vaniqi blames past neglect by various stakeholders for the perilous state of the Fijian sugar sector, maintaining that ‘the sugar industry is now faced with a bigger problem of trying to upgrade the sugar mills while having big debts to pay’. The military government of Fiji remains committed to the revival of the sugar sector, ‘as there is no other industry that can replace sugar’.</p><p>Meanwhile, the search goes on for a new CEO for FSC, with reports that international experts from other sugar-producing countries are being targeted. Changing patterns of ownership of FSC’s traditional trading partners in Europe are also generating uncertainty, following the takeover of Tate &amp; Lyle’s sugar operations by American Sugar Refiners (ASR), a Cuban-American owned multinational.</p><p>The critical situation of the mills and the need for their improvement was underlined when, in late December, the Labasa Mill struggled to complete its season. Furthermore, the Rarawai Mill’s crushing season, unusually, had to be extended to the first week of the new year, 2011.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Radio New Zealand International, ‘Fiji sugar industry woes seen as legacy of dirty politics’, 29 December 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&amp;id=57916" target="_self">http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&amp;id=57916</a><br/>
Radio New Zealand International, ‘Fiji Sugar Corporation makes changes at the top’, 27 December 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&amp;id=57887" target="_self">http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&amp;id=57887</a><br/>
Radio Fiji, ‘Sugar allocation to pay off FSC debts’, 24 December 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.radiofiji.com.fj/fullstory.php?id=33219" target="_self">http://www.radiofiji.com.fj/fullstory.php?id=33219</a><br/>
Fiji Broadcasting Corporation, ‘Labasa sugar mill struggles to end crushing 2010’, 29 December 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.radiofiji.com.fj/fullstory.php?id=33288" target="_self">http://www.radiofiji.com.fj/fullstory.php?id=33288</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With most of the available government funding being used to cover existing debt, the question arises as to whether financing will be available for covering operating cost and much needed capital renewal. This is particularly the case, given that a recent attempt to raise capital from the public and targeting the private sector did not achieve its target, even with a government guarantee. The production and processing difficulties are compounded by the evolving market situation which is radically transforming the attractiveness of the EU market and the changing corporate ownership patterns of EU-based sugar companies, many of which are increasingly global in their operations.</p><p>It is unclear where the Fijian sugar sector will situate itself in this evolving situation in the short term (see <i>Agritrade</i>&nbsp;article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Sugar-sector/News/Sugar-price-prospects-uncertain-but-looking-good" target="_self">Sugar price prospects uncertain, but looking good</a>’, January 2011), as well as the medium and long term (see <i>Agritrade</i>&nbsp;article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Sugar-sector/News/Report-published-on-prospects-for-sugar-markets-up-to-2030" target="_blank">Report published on prospects for sugar markets up to 2030</a>’, January 2011). Clearly, getting to grips with the new marketing challenges will be critical if commercial revenues are to be generated for the renewal of the industry, and if the Fijian sugar industry is to find a new place in the evolving global sugar market. While FSC executives have to date been struggling to get to grips with technical and operational problems, the quest for a CEO with international experience of repositioning an ACP sugar producer in an evolving market context suggests an emerging awareness of the need to get to grips with marketing issues.</p>
		</div>
		
